\section{GIS Overview}\label{gis-overview}

\begin{frame}{GIS Data: Vector Data}

One of the main GIS data types is vector data. Vectors (also called
shapefiles) consist of points, lines and polygons. These shapes are
attached to a dataframe, where each row corresponds to a different
spatial element.

\begin{center}\includegraphics[width=2.57in]{img/Attribute_Table} \end{center}

\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{GIS Data: Raster Data}

The second main GIS data type is raster data. Rasters are
spatially-referenced grids, where each grid has a value associated with
it.

\begin{center}\includegraphics[width=2.62in]{img/raster_r_example} \end{center}

\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Coordinate Reference Systems}

\textbf{Coordinate reference systems} map pairs of numbers to a
location.

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \textbf{Geographic Coordinate Systems} live on a sphere; here, the
  units are in decimal degrees

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Using the WGS84 coordinate system the World Bank MC building is
    located at 38.89 degrees latitude and -77.04 degrees longitude.
  \end{itemize}
\item
  \textbf{Projected Coordinate Systems} project the earth onto a flat
  surface. This
  \href{http://geoawesomeness.com/5-tools-will-let-master-map-projections/}{distorts}
  the earth in some way (shape, area, distance or direction)

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Using to the World Mercator projection, the World Bank is located
    4680364.64 north and -8576320.73 east.
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}\includegraphics[width=2.18in]{img/coordinate_systems} \end{center}

\end{frame}

\begin{frame}[fragile]{Make a Map}

We'll load the map data using the the readOGR function from the rgdal
package. The argument for dsn is the folder where the shapefile is and
layer is the name of the shapefile.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{library}\NormalTok{(rgdal)}
\NormalTok{worldmap <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{readOGR}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{dsn=}\NormalTok{finalData, }\DataTypeTok{layer=}\StringTok{"worldmap"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(worldmap)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\includegraphics{Lab_6_-_Spatial_Data_files/figure-beamer/unnamed-chunk-7-1.pdf}

\end{frame}
